right eye has a relative afferent pupillary defect. Fundoscopy is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Optic papillitis","Central retinal vein occlusion","Optic atrophy","Central retinal artery occlusion","Anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe optic disc shows florid disc swelling and early exudate at the macula consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic papillitis\u003C/strong\u003E. Optic papillitis is a subtype of optic neuritis involving inflammation of the optic nerve head. Optic papillitis is most commonly secondary to idiopathic inflammatory demyelination (i.e. multiple sclerosis). However, optic papillitis can also be secondary to infections such as cat-scratch disease or \u003Cem\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/em\u003E, Herpes zoster, Syphillis or TB. This patient has two cats at home, requiring exclusion of Cat scratch disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic atrophy\u003C/strong\u003E can occur secondary to a number of conditions causing damage to the optic nerve including compressive causes (e.g. tumours, thyroid eye disease), ischaemia and glaucoma. Optic atrophy presents with vision loss and a characteristic pale optic disc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E presents with painless reduction in vision, with the fundus examination showing retinal haemorrhages in all four quadrants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E presents in an older age group with painless vision loss, with the fundus showing a pale, swollen retina and a cherry red spot at the macula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior ischaemic optic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is also more common in an older age group, often with multiple cardiovascular risk factors. Presentation is with painless vision loss and a swollen optic disc.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Painful vision loss associated with a swollen optic disc supports a diagnosis of optic papillitis."],"references":["Pflipsen M, Massaquoi M, Wolf S. Evaluation of the Painful Eye. Am Fam Physician. 2016; 93:991-98."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29017"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"490"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1940"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1940"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/802065fe-9a2c-4060-b7ab-afb6c9e35437.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/802065fe-9a2c-4060-b7ab-afb6c9e35437.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":533,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29017"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-05T17:05:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-05T17:05:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"490"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44036"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"